            <div class="scrollable-area">
                <p><strong></strong>In the later West Saxon dialect, spellings with the diphthong 'ie' were often spelled with a 'y' instead. So 'hieran' became 'hyran'.</p>
                <p><strong></strong>This spelling of <em>þegen</em> is actually a mistake. The correct spelling is written in above the word in the manuscript.</p>
                <p><strong></strong>Thither has fallen out of common usage in modern English, but it means 'towards there', specifically away from the speaker.</p>
                <p><strong></strong>An ealdorman was an official in Anglo-Saxon England. They were usually appointed by the king and were responsible for a specific shire.</p>
